    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Sept<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 15<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>
                        1778</dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It will always give me real pleasure to contribute to your amusement: I lament
                    that the evil days we have the misfortune to see, must stop our litterary
                    luxuries. Before the dreadful prospect opened,<note type="editorial">America
                        declared independence from Britain on 4 July 1776. France allied with the
                        Americans early in 1778.</note> I had put a <rs type="art" ref="ardb.xml#ar0006">drawing of old <persName ref="pe0321">Sir
                            John Wynn</persName> of <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0760">Gwedir</placeName>
                    </rs> from a fine original at <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0761">Wynnstay</placeName>
                    <note type="editorial">Sir John Wynn, first baronet (1553–1627), of Gwydir,
                        Llanrwst. A plate of 'Sir John Wynne, Bart. from the original at Wynne-Stay'
                        is included in A tour in Wales (1st edn., [1778]), vol. II [ECCO; ABBR.], p.
                        140. It was engraved by William Sharp.</note> into <persName ref="pe0014">an artist</persName>'s<note type="editorial">This may
                        be Moses Griffith, who was employed by Thomas Pennant from 1769.
                        ODNB.</note> hands. when that is finished, proofs will be at yr service. if
                    I visit town next spring I shall not fail waiting on you, being with the truest
                    esteem</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Dear Sir <lb/>Y<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>
                    </salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">Tho.
                    Pennant</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>excuse the liberty I take in begging that the inclosed may be returned
                        directed to <lb/>the <persName ref="pe0322">Rev<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> John
                            Jones</persName>
                        <lb/>Fellow of <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0762">Jesus College
                            <lb/>oxford</placeName>
                        <note type="editorial">John Jones, a graduate of Jesus College, Oxford, was
                            named by Pennant for his 'indefatigble [work] in furnishing me with
                            extracts from the manuscripts of the university’ in the Advertisement to
                            A Tour in Wales. MDCCLXX (London: Henry Hughes, 1778),
                        iii–iv.</note>.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>

